However today I have a long train journey with two children who will be engrossed in their tech, so its a good day to stick my toe into the shallows at least of Taylor Swift.

But where? What is her best album? All suggestions appreciated.

  2. Bingo Little says

    20/10/2023 at 10:33

    If you want straight Pop Taylor start with 1989.

    If you want Synth-Pop Taylor start with Midnights.

    If you want Country-tinged Taylor start with Red.

    If you want tasteful, beard-stroking backwoods Proper Music Actually Taylor start with Evermore or Folklore (the conventional Afterword jumping-on points).

    If you want the greatest break up/kiss off lyric of its generation start with the peerless All Too Well (10 Minute Version).

  3. Black Type says

    20/10/2023 at 11:27

    Folkmore, as Swifties call the ‘sister’ albums, are indeed the recognised go-to for people who consider her as ‘just for teens’ etc.
    I recently listened to Midnights again for the first time in ages. It’s an astounding album, sonically fascinating and lyrically rich and sophisticated.
    I’d put Speak Now on the same level as Red in terms of style and quality – both incorporating elements of country, pop and even stadium rock.
    If you want to experience a curveball, try Reputation – harder electronic soundscapes based around rap, hip-hop, trap, but retaining her emotional storytelling core.
    For a more country-focused vibe, Fearless is where she begins to mature as a songwriter and artist. On the debut, the potential is all there, but it naturally sounds still a little gauche.

    The other choices you need to make are over the original albums or the Taylor’s Versions. The originals have the immediacy and freshness of being recorded in the moment, but the TVs benefit from her improved vocals and greater studio experience.

            • Bingo Little says

              24/10/2023 at 14:25

              I’m a big Chaplin fan, but I don’t take it as a given that he’d even make it onto our screens if he was starting out today.

              As with most stars of popular culture, his skillset was uniquely suited to the particular moment in which he arrived. It’s certainly difficult to point to anyone in movies now who is his obvious heir, or who trades in the same material he did – just as virtually no one (in the mainstream at least) is making music that particularly attempts to sound like the Beatles. They’re artists of their time.

              By the same logic, I don’t think it’s a given that Taylor Swift would have been a success if she’d touched down in 1963, or was catapulted forward in time to 2083 for that matter. Tastes move on and it’s difficult enough to achieve spectacular success in your own times, let alone someone else’s.

              The major pop stars of the day will always cause and reflect social change, and then the world eventually moves on. It’s just the nature of things.

  9. hedgepig says

    21/10/2023 at 06:07

    Red tends to get a bit underrated, I think, but it’s the first hint of an intentional transition away from the Nashville-with-sequins Shania-isms of the early template, and it’s packed with great songs. (I don’t mean that in a sniffy way: Shania Twain was a huge influence on her early on, and nothing at all wrong with that, but it kept her audience narrower than it needed to be).

    Anyway, it’s a cracking album. I can live without its top and tail, but from the title track through to Sad Beautiful Tragic, it’s almost nothing but net (The Last Time, Everything has Changed and Begin Again being my skips). You want Taylor’s Version, natch, and the 10 min All Too Well is one of the only pop songs I’ve ever heard that justifies the run time. It’s cinematic, compelling stuff.

    You don’t tend to listen to Taylor Swift for her voice, which is pleasant but not remarkable: she’s got a real gift for melody, but IMV it’s the lyrics that make her special. She’s incredibly good at specific, richly textured observation, with a real gift for nailing emotional truths in a few words, and Red is the record where that talent starts to become really obvious (I Almost Do and All Too Well being the clearest examples). With Lana del Rey, I think she’s the best lyricist working today, and has been for some time.

      Ah, the Albarn perspective – which was given a deserved kicking at the time. She endured this snarky criticism early in her career, so wrote the whole of Speak Now completely on her own as a “fuck you” to the naysayers.

      Yes, she does collaborate – and readily acknowledges it and gives credit where it’s due. But don’t take that to imply she’s a peripheral presence in the creative process; all her collaborators are on record that she is absolutely the creative driver of all the songwriting, coming up with most of the compositional blueprints and writing 99.5% of all the lyrics.

      I hate the implication which *still* persists that as a woman, she cannot possibly be a ‘proper’ artist and her success is due to shadowy figures in the background. No-one undermines the pale, stale, male ‘icons’ in such a way, when indeed most of them are celebrated as co-writers.

      Log in to Reply
